Take a good look at my happy place. 

This is what the greenhouse will look like in just a couple of months. 

The geraniums are overwintering and the first set of seeds will be sown at the end of January or first week of February. 

I'm getting a knee replacement sometime in February, at least that's the plan so seed sowing will be very interesting this year! 

I'm also hoping to start some geranium plants from cuttings this month. 

It amazes me how quickly my life went from Christmas to gardening within just a week or so. 

Who is ready for gardening season? 🌼

Winter is all about nesting for me. ❄️

Many of us are ready to jump right over the winter season into spring.

I am so excited about being on the garden again. Even more so now that the sweet peas are growing in the greenhouse. 

But I'm thinking differently this year. Using my word for 2023, gratitude, I'm looking at the brighter side of winter.

I'm grateful to have this down time to plan, get organized, and slow down a bit.

What about you? What makes you grateful for winter?

I'm sowing my cosmos seeds tomorrow!

They are one of my favorite cut flowers in my garden and are so easy to grow. 

Cosmos are easily grown from seed and will even survive in poor soil conditions. 🌸

Pollinators love these beautiful blooms. 🦋🐝

Cosmos are drought tolerant. 

They have a long bloom time in the cut flower garden. 

Have you grown cosmos before? If so, what's your favorite variety to grow? 

Visit my blog for more info on growing and caring for cosmos.

Looking for an easy, last minute flower arrangement idea for Easter? 

I found some potted spring flowering bulbs at the garden center that fit perfectly inside my vintage enamel container.🌷🌼🪻 

An old tree in my backyard had plenty of moss, so I mixed it in. 

You can either plant all the potted flowers in a thrifted container using potting soil and display on your porch afterwards. The bulbs will continue to bloom every year. 🪻

Or you can do what I did and just place the pots inside the large container, hiding the plastic pots with moss. Then, if you're hosting the holiday gathering, hand out the potted spring bulbs to your guests when they're leaving. 🌷
